      "content": "Rising stars, high stakes in Turkey vs. Paraguay World Cup matchSan Francisco Chronicle LogoHearst Newspapers LogoSkip to main contentSportsTurkey vs. Paraguay: Rising stars, secret language and high stakes for World Cup matchNext up on Levi’s Stadium’s World Cup slate is a Group D showdown between Turkey and Paraguay, two teams with unique strengths that cannot afford to lose on Friday.By Noah Furtado, Staff WriterJune 18, 2026Juan Jose Caceres, left, and his Paraguay teammates allowed an uncharacteristic four goals in a loss to the U.S. men and Malik Tillman in their World Cup Group D match last Friday at SoFi Stadium.Andre Penner/Associated PressThe stakes have only increased with the second matches of World Cup group stage play underway. Turkey and Paraguay are next to play at Levi’s Stadium, taking the field on Friday night. They find themselves at the bottom of what was viewed as a tight Group D, which the U.S. men’s national team and Australia currently pace.The top two finishers in each group automatically advance to the knockout round. Then the top eight of 12 third-place teams sneak in. That means the stakes for Friday’s match are especially high; both Turkey and Paraguay have to rebound from their initial, stunning losses. The Turks entered the tournament as favorites on paper, but in spite of their star power fell handily to the Aussies in a 2-0 decision. Paraguay’s La Albirroja, or “The White and Red” in English, surrendered a whopping four goals to the Americans; such a leaky back line is completely uncharacteristic of Paraguayan football.AdvertisementArticle continues below this adThe brilliance of young attacking midfielders Arda Güler and Kenan Yildiz got Turkey back into the World Cup for the first time since 2002. Perhaps the moment was too big in their opener. Friday night has to be a different story regardless of those high expectations. Turkey made the semifinals and finished third in 2002.It’s also been a minute since Paraguay qualified. The Chronicle recently reported on the stir felt among Paraguayans. This is their national side’s first World Cup in 16 years.San Francisco Chronicle LogoSee more S.F. Chronicle on GoogleMake us a Preferred Source to get more of our news when you search.Add Preferred SourceHere are the story lines to know for Thursday.Despite superior firepower, Turkey and midfielder Arda Güler were held scoreless in an opening loss to Australia in their World Cup Group D match on Saturday in Vancouver, British Columbia.Abbie Parr/Associated PressRising stars: Güler and Yildiz are already stars. The “rising” part is more of a misnomer because of their age. Güler turned 21 in February; Yildiz turned 21 in May. AdvertisementArticle continues below this adMore For YouJordanian fans celebrate World Cup debut in solidarity with Palestinian neighbors: ‘We’re one country’Jordan’s first World Cup appearance is a big deal in that country, but the team also has the support of Palestinians, with fans from both groups voicing their support at Levi’s Stadium on...FIFA suggests Levi’s Stadium near 99% full for its World Cup opener. Empty seats show otherwiseQatar forced a draw against Switzerland in a Bay Area World Cup opening match that met the moment, but depending on who you ask, turnout at Levi’s Stadium was just OK.Güler has played for La Liga powerhouse Real Madrid since he was 18, tallying 42 combined goals and assists to date. Yildiz debuted for prestigious Serie A side Juventus at 18 and has since collected 43 combined goals and assists. Nothing is normal about those numbers.In a surprising development, Yildiz was not in the starting lineup for the Australia match. He subbed in at halftime. Güler started and took eight shots, including three on goal that were saved. Yildiz attempted six shots in the second half. Turkey as a team finished with 30 shots (to nine for Australia) and seven on target, 1.66 expected goals (xG), and also dominated possession (62.9%) in an otherwise scoreless showing.The Turks have the talent to appear in the round of 32. They just need the execution.Guaraní: Paraguay is a bilingual country that speaks both Spanish and an indigenous South American language called Guaraní; according to the 2022 Permanent Household Survey of the National Institute of Statistics, up to 70% of the Paraguayan population over the age of 5 speaks Guaraní. Few populations outside of Paraguay’s speak the language.AdvertisementArticle continues below this adNational team players utilize Guaraní to their advantage on the pitch.“It’s a language that if you’re not Paraguayan you won’t understand, and Paraguay actually use this as a tactic in soccer,” said Eduardo Gustale, vice minister of the Investment and Export Network in Paraguay. “So even if someone understands Spanish, you’ll hear a Paraguayan speaking Guarani… and that’s how they tell each other the different plays and the tactics.”Communication is all-important in football, especially for Paraguayan football, which has…",
